[This report is a preliminary version of the computational results included in the paper. Only instances generated with option spheredown are used since they are hard instances.]

[See https://rstudio.github.io/distill/ on how to write this report.]

All instances are minimized, i.e. if an objective function \(z(x)\) is maximized, we minimize \(-z(x)\) instead. Note that in all instances only binary variables are considered.

In this section we report on the computational experiments conducted with the tri–objective branch–and–bound algorithm. All algorithms have been implemented in Julia \(1.0.1\). The experiments have been done on a computer with an Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-8700 CPU @ 3.20GHz processor and 32GB of RAM memory [check if correct].

The algorithm can be run using algorithm configuration parameters nS, vS, oB and eps where

[explanation of the different configurations with possible refs to sections in paper]

[Add other implementation details, e.g. about Bensolve and possible numerical instabilities]

The purpose of the computational study is to answer the following questions:

[Just some ideas for the moment. Add/modify as you like]

  1. What is the performance of the different algorithm configurations?
  2. Which algorithm configurations perform the best?
  3. Is it worth doing objective branching?
  4. How do node selection, variable selection and objective branching affect the performance of the algorithm?
  5. In which subprocedures are the cpu time used?
  6. How are nodes pruned?
  7. Where in the tree do we use obj branching avg + min and max values (relative values and box plot)?
  8. Depth of tree in AP vs KP?
  9. Do integer rounding improve the performance?
  10. How is the performance of the tri-objective B&B algorithm compared to objective branching algorithms?

Statistic: Number of nodes in the tree relative to total possible given depth

Detailed results for each instance

Detailed results for each instance can be generated using instance.Rmd. The report is already generated for some of the instances (see links in the table with input statistics). Some instances that might be of interest:

  • Instances with lowest number of nondominated points: Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_10, Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_2_10, Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_2_2
  • Instances with highest number of nondominated points (solved): Forget20-KP_30_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_10, Forget20-KP_30_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_8, Forget20-UFLP_7_3_1-1000_1-100_spheredown_1_1
  • Instances with lowest unsupported nondominated points percentage: Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_2_10, Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_2_2, Forget20-KP_10_3_1-1000_spheredown_2_8
  • Instances with highest unsupported nondominated points percentage: Forget20-AP_8_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_10, Forget20-AP_8_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_2, Forget20-AP_8_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_3
  • Instances with highest supported non-extreme nondominated points percentage: Forget20-AP_6_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_1, Forget20-AP_6_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_10, Forget20-AP_6_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_2
  • Instances with highest variance in cpu time: Forget20-AP_8_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_2, Forget20-AP_8_3_1-1000_spheredown_1_3, Forget20-UFLP_6_3_1-1000_1-100_spheredown_1_8
